ular name for silicosis, provides a powerful metaphor for the danger, wasting, and loss that penetrated mining life. Finn explores themes of privation and privilege, trust and betrayal, and offers a new model for community studies that links local culture and global capitalism.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aCopper industry and tradexSocial aspectsxChilexChuquicamataxChilexChuquicamataxMontanaxButte. 0aCopper industry and tradexSocial aspectsxMontanaxButte. 0aCopper industry and tradexSocial aspectszChilezChilezMontanaxChuquicamataxButte. 0aCopper industry and tradexSocial aspectszChilezChuquicamata. 0aCopper industry and tradexSocial aspectszMontanazButte. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh  aanaconda company.  aanthropology.  abetrayal.  abusiness.  abutte.  acapitalism.  achile.  achuquicamata.  aclass.  acommunity studies.  acommunity.  aconsumption.  acopper mining.  acopper production.  acultural boundaries.  adanger.  aethnography.  agender.  ageographic boundaries.  aglobal capitalism.  alocal culture.  aminers.  amining community.  amining history.  amining life.  amining men.  amining.  amontana.  anational boundaries.  apolitics.  aprivation.  aprivilege.  asilicosis.  asocial history.  atransformation.  awasting.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Package Archive Pre-2000z97831106353480 cprintz978052021137740uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/9780520920071?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520920071423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520920071/original  a978-3-11-063534-8  University of California Press Package Archive Pre-2000b2000  aEBA_EMB  aGBV-deGruyter-alles